CH. VII. Haudproculinde] It is a comparatively modern notion (perhaps an inserence from Gen. xiv. 3) that the Cities of the Plain were submerged: they are always described as burnt and left desolate : see esp. Gen. xix. 28.

fulminum jactu] A perhaps legitimate rationalisation os the scriptural story, in the form that it had been told to him: cf. igne caelesti in ξ 3. Orosius, who (i. 5) quotes the passage, has ac- cording to some MSS. ictu for jactu.

2 Nam cuncta, etc.] An in- accurate version of the story of the ‘apples of Sodom,' which looked like eatable fruit, but turned to ashes in the mouth. This no doubt

was a fanciful description of some real plant or plants of the district ; modern botanists have not certainly determined which.
